# Fluff Date: 2026-02-13 13:54:40
overview:<p>The Gurkha is a thirty-five-ton light BattleMech developed by the Word of Blake on Terra in the early 3060s. Following his promotion in 3061, the Blakist Precentor Martial issued a call for new light and medium designs to keep the refurbished Krupp Armament Works factory running at capacity. Among several submissions, the most promising was a fast striker built around the improved C3i computer network and a melee weapon, a sword designed for up-close combat. Approved for production and named after the famed Terran commandos known for their loyalty and blade work, the Gurkha entered full production in early 3063.</p><p>The design quickly became popular among Word of Blake Militia light 'Mech pilots, drawing MechWarriors who favored aggressive close-quarters engagements. The Gurkha's combination of networking capability and physical combat potential gave the Blakist Militia a distinctive tactical asset during the Civil War and Jihad eras, though production ceased following the Coalition's capture of Terra.</p>

capabilities:<p>Built on a lightweight Krupp 255 endo steel chassis and powered by a Magna 245 XL engine, the Gurkha achieves a top speed of nearly 119 kilometers per hour, exceptional for a design carrying seven and a half tons of Krupp 155 armor. This combination of speed and protection makes the Gurkha remarkably difficult to bring down for its weight class, though the absence of jump jets limits its maneuverability in rough or urban terrain.</p><p>The Gurkha's primary tactical value stems from its Exeter Longscan 500 communications system integrated with a C3i computer. Operating within a six-unit network, the 'Mech can close with enemy targets and provide precise targeting data to its heavier lancemates, enabling the entire formation to fire with devastating accuracy. A Fusigon Longtooth ER PPC provides surprisingly potent long-range firepower for a light 'Mech, while four Diverse Optics extended-range small lasers and a broadsword deliver punishing damage at close quarters.</p><p>The design's principal weakness is that opponents who recognize the C3i threat will prioritize Gurkhas for immediate elimination. The exposed actuators in the 'Mech's arms represent an additional vulnerability, and the lack of jump jets can leave a Gurkha stranded when terrain restricts its ground speed advantage.</p>

deployment:<p>The most radical redesign of the Gurkha, this 3069 variant strips the entire original weapons suite and replaces it with a snub-nose PPC, three ER medium lasers, and a single ER small laser. The traditional sword gives way to a retractable blade, and the addition of Triple Strength Myomer dramatically increases the 'Mech's physical combat damage when operating at elevated heat levels. This configuration pushes the Gurkha firmly into the role of a close-quarters brawler, sacrificing the base model's long-range capability for devastating performance inside three hundred meters.</p>

history:<p>The Gurkha's origins trace to the Word of Blake's consolidation of Terran military industry following ComStar's schism. The Krupp Armament Works in Germany had already begun producing Raijins for the Blakist Militia, but idle assembly capacity prompted calls for additional designs. The Gurkha was selected from several competing proposals in 3061 and entered production by early 3063, filling a need for a networked light striker in the expanding Word of Blake Militia.</p><p>During the FedCom Civil War, Gurkhas were deployed alongside Vanquishers to form the core of C3i-linked combat networks. This pairing proved highly effective, with the fast-moving Gurkhas providing forward targeting data while heavier 'Mechs delivered concentrated fire on designated targets. The sword (adopted as a symbol of pride and fanaticism within the Militia) became closely associated with the Word of Blake's martial identity, appearing on unit insignia and dress uniforms.</p><p>The onset of the Jihad in 3067 saw continued and expanded Gurkha production at the Krupp facility. New variants incorporating advanced weaponry entered service as the conflict intensified, reflecting the Word of Blake's access to cutting-edge Terran military technology. Gurkhas served in Blakist formations across multiple theaters, their C3i networks making them force multipliers in combined-arms engagements even as Coalition forces increasingly learned to target the networked light 'Mechs early in any engagement.</p><p>The fall of Terra to the allied Coalition brought an end to Gurkha production. The Krupp Armament Works survived the fighting largely intact, but the victorious Republic of the Sphere deactivated the production lines. No subsequent faction has resumed manufacture of the design, leaving surviving Gurkhas as an increasingly rare sight on battlefields of the Dark Age and ilClan eras, maintained only through salvage and cannibalization of existing stocks.</p>

